---
description: Review Serbian Cyrillic translations in countries.json for natural language quality and child-appropriateness — run after any bulk translation batch, before committing
alwaysApply: false
---

Read `src/EduMap.Api/Data/countries.json`. Find all countries with `translations.sr-Cyrl.name`. Sample 20 randomly (or all if fewer than 20).

**Reviewer persona:** Native Serbian speaker checking text that Una (7 years old, reads Cyrillic fluently) will read aloud in the app. The bar: natural, warm phrasing — the kind a parent or teacher uses. She should be able to read any entry without stumbling.

**Flag if any of these are true:**

- Sounds like word-for-word machine translation — stiff phrasing, unnatural word order, dictionary-style
- Any Latin characters appear in a Cyrillic field (script mixing is always a data bug)
- `funFact` contains vocabulary a 7-year-old Serbian speaker is unlikely to know
- Country name or capital uses an unusual transliteration instead of the standard Serbian Cyrillic form

**Output format — one line per flagged entry:**

```
ISO2 | field | what's wrong | suggested rewrite
```

**End with a summary:**

- Total reviewed · Total flagged
- Verdict: **Good** (≤10% flagged) / **Needs work** (10–30%) / **Poor** (>30%)

A flag without a suggested rewrite is not actionable — always include one.
